(10 comments)

Generally agree with the data model for 'app'.

Don't agree that we need to expose individual workflow actions in the resource. Also, the current the way actions resource is defined, it will not be able to support workflows that contain multiple actions (test, test+build, test+build+deploy, build+deploy, deploy).

I suggest we be opinionated and support only above 5 workflows to begin with. We introduce a top-level workflow resource named 'workflows' 

GET /workflows/

which returns a json that defines each of these workflows with a name and an id.

We modify app registration to take input the workflow name and/or id corresponding to the workflow that we want to associate that app with. We could associate multiple workflows with an app.

Then we introduce a sub-resource named something like 'triggerworkflow' for an app. We use this to trigger a specific workflow for the app.

POST /apps/<app-uuid>/triggerworkflow

{
  workflow_name: test
}

Getting information for a triggered workflow could be done as follows:

GET /apps/<app-uuid>/triggerworkflow/<workflow-id>

{
   id: <workflow-id>
   workflow_name: test
   status: QUEUED
}"}, {'account_id': 1375, 'date': '2015-05-14 15:30:27.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6: Workflow-1

commit_message:
App resource

Introduces a first-order resource, the app, to manage Solum applications
and replace the assembly and plan resources.
Includes an 'actions' model to allow for richer configuration of workflows
and better tracking of artifacts and application changes.

blueprint app-resource

Change-Id: Iedd00827461f6fb6bb98c209673700053fade53e

commit_message:
Cleanup exceptions

We have a general problem with syncing exceptions from oslo-incubator
because whilst each project ends up with an exception named the same -
they are not the same object and cannot be caught in a unified way.

As we push session to be the default transport mechanism this is
becoming more and more of a problem as each client needs to do it's own
exception handling so that the exception in its tree is raised and not
break compatibility.

We need to structure keystone exceptions as if keystoneclient is the
base dependency for all other clients and allow them to import the
session exceptions on there own in such that we can start reusing these
objects across clients.

Change-Id: Ic8a041262105ab9859539b0410c41ec42ab2b2a9

[{'created': '2015-05-12 06:34:30.000000000', 'message': 'Add cleanup after creating keypair

There is no cleanup added after a keypair is created in test case
test_create_specify_keypair in test_servers.py which causes the test
case to leave behind a keypair when allow_tenant_isolation is false.
This issue is not observed when allow_tenant_isolation is true and
admin credentials are provided in tempest.conf as the tenant itself is
deleted after the test case ends.

Closes-Bug:1453112
Change-Id: Ia17f4dd2585c0d51540b05bcd9e08eec2757c1dd
Signed-off-by: ahmad <afaheem88@gmail.com>
'}]
commit_message:
Add cleanup after creating keypair

There is no cleanup added after a keypair is created in test case
test_create_specify_keypair in test_servers.py which causes the test
case to leave behind a keypair when allow_tenant_isolation is false.
This issue is not observed when allow_tenant_isolation is true and
admin credentials are provided in tempest.conf as the tenant itself is
deleted after the test case ends.

Closes-Bug:1453112
Change-Id: Ia17f4dd2585c0d51540b05bcd9e08eec2757c1dd
Signed-off-by: ahmad <afaheem88@gmail.com>

Add a small documentation paragraph about the operating system elements,
what they are required to provide (and thus what other elements can rely
on).

This makes DISTRO_NAME a prime-class variable, which can now be assumed

commit_message:
doc: small snippet about operating system elements

Add a small documentation paragraph about the operating system elements,
what they are required to provide (and thus what other elements can rely
on).

This makes DISTRO_NAME a prime-class variable, which can now be assumed
to always exists (it was de-facto required so far).

Change-Id: Iffbc69de0516b58bfde48e87cd73073428d66b05

We should make use of the CentOS-7-x86_64-GenericCloud.qcow2 symlink from
http://cloud.centos.org/centos/7/images/ instead of having a hard coded cloud
image. Specific cloud images can still be downloaded by overriding
$DIB_RELEASE.

More importantly, using the symlink will keep us automatically up to date with

commit_message:
Use Centos 7 cloud image symlink

We should make use of the CentOS-7-x86_64-GenericCloud.qcow2 symlink from
http://cloud.centos.org/centos/7/images/ instead of having a hard coded cloud
image. Specific cloud images can still be downloaded by overriding
$DIB_RELEASE.

More importantly, using the symlink will keep us automatically up to date with
the latest CentOS 7 cloud image. The image in use by the hard coded value
occassionally exhibits "No space left on device" errors after the cloud-init
filesystem resize. More info about this issue is at:
http://xfs.org/index.php/XFS_FAQ#Q:_Why_do_I_receive_No_space_left_on_device_after_xfs_growfs.3F

The newer cloud image (with a newer kernel) does not exhibit this issue.

Change-Id: I3e19f6269ceba937fcd630bab265d132bd525519

commit_message:
[install-guide] [yum] use apache front-end for keystone

Replace default eventlet front-end with Apache front-end to provide
a more production-style deployment.

Partially implements bp installguide-kilo.

Change-Id: Ie5e128b6f94e29e9ef216ea668284756a69ec2b7

commit_message:
puppet: use a single image for CI

This patch updates the Puppet CI job so that it uses the new
disk_image.yaml functionality in devtest to use a single
image for all of the Overcloud roles. This should help
save CI time and also significantly cleans up how
we configure the puppet CI job.

Depends-On: I1b1dbd5a7e2a4fda2eff31813518df8bc72e7e56

Change-Id: I11c2674391834ec09e0b029a3f9b181b8456de8b

commit_message:
Add a puppet disk images YAML file

This patch adds a puppet version of the new disk_image.yaml
file which can be used to drive build-images and load-images
via devtest_overcloud.sh.

The overcloud_puppet_disk_images.yaml currently builds a
single image that is configured to be used for all
puppet roles.

Also, includes doc updates to show how this simplifies
the using puppet w/ devtest_overcloud.sh.

Change-Id: I1b1dbd5a7e2a4fda2eff31813518df8bc72e7e56

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-05-20 17:43:39.000000000', 'message': "Publish Libcloud version of FirstApp

The Libcloud version of FirstApp is ready to move from draft stage
so it can be widely disseminated to satiate the burning need for this
content that is currently not being addressed. The guide will be
promoted heavily leading into and at the summit.

So far it has received significantly more editing and testing than
other sprint-created documents when they were published. This is thanks
to the work of: Andreas Jaegar, Karen Bradshaw, Diane Fleming, Shilla Saebi,
James Dempsey's users, Jon Proulx, Bruno Lago, Chuck Burkett, Dana Bauer,
and the original authors (at least 2 each section).

Any areas lacking in the guide are well understood and captured in the
bug list:
https://bugs.launchpad.net/openstack-manuals/+bugs?field.tag=firstapp
and there are no major blockers that would prevent listing this guide
on developer.openstack.org.

This patch links the libcloud section of developer.openstack.org to the
guide.

Change-Id: If85bc020cd54e3ca06e5d320024dec9428764641

received during it's packed-room summit sesion.

to the work of: Andreas Jaegar, Karen Bradshaw, Diane Fleming, Shilla Saebi,

and the original authors (at least 2 each section).

commit_message:
Publish Libcloud version of FirstApp

The Libcloud version of FirstApp is ready to move from draft stage
so it can be widely disseminated to satiate the burning need for this
content that is currently not being addressed. The guide was very well
received during it's packed-room summit sesion.

So far it has received significantly more editing and testing than
other sprint-created documents when they were published. This is thanks
to the work of: Andreas Jaegar, Karen Bradshaw, Diane Fleming, Shilla Saebi,
James Dempsey's users, Jon Proulx, Bruno Lago, Chuck Burkett, Dana Bauer,
and the original authors (at least 2 each section).

Any areas lacking in the guide are well understood and captured in the
bug list:
https://bugs.launchpad.net/openstack-manuals/+bugs?field.tag=firstapp
and there are no major blockers that would prevent listing this guide
on developer.openstack.org.

This patch links the libcloud section of developer.openstack.org to the
guide.

Change-Id: If85bc020cd54e3ca06e5d320024dec9428764641

commit_message:
Increase Kolla build timeout by 30 minutes

The latest full build attempt was terminated at 90 minutes, so increase
by 30 minutes. I personally am hopeful that once we get image building
verification passing in the gate, we can start focusing on using a cache
to speed up this process significantly.

Change-Id: I9f8252133d460e5042ea88a67cf11546b2164a0d

Import xattr with sudo early on

[{'created': '2015-05-18 22:13:38.000000000', 'message': "SSP: get host_uuid from disk driver

The previous algorithm of parsing the LPAR's AssociatedManagedSystem to
retrieve the UUID of the host was unnecessarily complex.  This change
set simply uses the self.host_uuid available from the disk driver.

Change-Id: I2fe1e93b7039383889e56b809d5348ee2d5222a9
"}, {'created': '2015-05-19 21:32:59.000000000', 'message': "SSP: Only consider this host's VIOSes

Previously, the SSP disk driver was gleaning the list of VIOS UUIDs from
the list of Nodes in the Cluster, and optionally restricting that list
to VIOSes from a specified host.

It will almost never be useful to know about VIOSes residing on a
different host.  Any attempt to talk to those VIOSes through the PowerVM
API will fail, as we don't have a pypowervm connection to that host.

Therefore this change set simplifies the retrieval of VIOS UUIDs,
eliminating the host_uuid option and restricting the result to VIOSes on
the current host.

Change-Id: I2fe1e93b7039383889e56b809d5348ee2d5222a9
"}]
commit_message:
SSP: Only consider this host's VIOSes

Previously, the SSP disk driver was gleaning the list of VIOS UUIDs from
the list of Nodes in the Cluster, and optionally restricting that list
to VIOSes from a specified host.

It will almost never be useful to know about VIOSes residing on a
different host.  Any attempt to talk to those VIOSes through the PowerVM
API will fail, as we don't have a pypowervm connection to that host.

Therefore this change set simplifies the retrieval of VIOS UUIDs,
eliminating the host_uuid option and restricting the result to VIOSes on
the current host.

Change-Id: I2fe1e93b7039383889e56b809d5348ee2d5222a9

commit_message:
Mistral bash completion script optimization

Make bash completion script generated automatically by using  'mistral
bash-completion' commands

Add a unit test for 'bash-completion' command.

Partially Implements: blueprint bash-completion-script-optimization
Change-Id: I97b15a1b9f41f98f5928f8bda4769957a37678d2

commit_message:
Fix devstack back to rabbit

Found the root of the problem: 
  Heat-engine uses queue 'engine' in rabbit, therefore we
  need to rename our queue in order to increase uniqueness 

Closes-Bug: #1324967

Change-Id: Iaf8a8f9f0357ae15ee4fc47d0031572a162526e6

commit_message:
Add bash-completion command support

Implement a helper command 'mistral bash-completion' to generate available
commands and options supported by mistral.

Change-Id: Id0e52daf4ee3f7c1ba9fefaa4f103bd74e66d97d
Partically Implements: blueprint bash-completion-script-optimization

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 11564, 'date': '2015-05-06 17:23:10.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

I grant that given the current state of the universe this is a reasonable set of guidelines for evaluating changes.

However in alternate universes you could imagine opportunities for being both more strict and more relaxed:

* if we were using versioned media types then any given api endpoint could behave somewhat differently based on the media type chosen but the shape of the api itself would remain static (thus addressing some of the properties concerns)
* if we were using hypermedia (fill in your own personal version of nirvana here)
* if we were in a type of universe I don't really have a name for at the what-uri-am-i-requesting and what-response-codes-am-i-expecting levels we would never change that except in some kind of major version way except to fix what can be clearly called bugs, but all that assumes that we've made good URI design decisions early on about our resources

Those are not the universes we're in and I'm not sure there's any clear path between where we are now and any of those, so some good rules of thumb (as described by the doc) seems about right."}, {'account_id': 10670, 'date': '2015-05-06 18:21:40.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

(1 comment)

Ryan and Chris, thanks for the comments.

and yea, i agree with your thoughts Chris. i'm not sure how we get to *that* universe but my hope is that we would evolve these guidelines as we get closer to it. 

or maybe we need to use these guidelines to move towards that place?"}, {'account_id': 12321, 'date': '2015-05-06 20:24:11.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 7, 'date': '2015-05-06 21:01:03.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

thanks for the comments Jay, i have a few questions about the best ways to proceed on some of them.'}, {'account_id': 970, 'date': '2015-05-07 16:15:15.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 10670, 'date': '2015-05-08 03:56:35.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 2750, 'date': '2015-05-11 18:09:19.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1

honestly, for historical reason, I'd say we should just import this as is as the base point. Then change history can be recorded from this base version.

Maybe we list it as "historical" before the changes get listed, but I'd rather see the evolution from what we have to where we are headed as more discreet changes.'}, {'account_id': 7, 'date': '2015-05-11 18:45:04.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Sean, you make a good point about tracking historical stuff. Mike, if you could somehow denote this as being a historical starting point taken from the openstack.org wiki, I'd be OK with this and using individual followup patches to argue specific points.

Best,

-jay"}, {'account_id': 1112, 'date': '2015-05-11 22:39:42.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

commit_message:
Adding guideline for evaluating api changes

This change converts the wiki page for evaluating api changes[1] into a
guideline. The content of the page has been kept largely the same aside
from a few grammar and consistency changes. One example has been removed
as the link to the bug and review had been abandoned. The questions have
also been removed as these seemed out of place for a guideline.

[1]: https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/APIChangeGuidelines

Change-Id: I5485970686e352d5146bcfe2a3cf53388b929b04

'}, {'created': '2015-03-11 14:01:50.000000000', 'message': 'Detach volume after deleting the instance

If an instance is booted from volume and goes in to error state due to
some reason. Volume from which instance is booted, remains in-use state
even the instance is deleted because instance has no host associated
with it.

Called _local_delete() to detach volume and destroy bdm if instance is
in error state and has no host associated with it. This will cleanup
both volumes and the networks.

Closes-Bug: #1404867

commit_message:
Detach volume after deleting instance with no host

If an instance is booted from a volume, shelved, and goes into an error
state due to some reason. Volume from which instance is booted, remains
in-use state even the instance is deleted because instance has no host
associated with it.

Called _local_delete() to detach volume and destroy bdm if instance is
in shelved_offloaded state or has no host associated with it. This will
cleanup both volumes and the networks.

Currently in test_servers.py, "test_delete_server_instance" executes
similar to "test_delete_server_instance_while_building". This is because
"test_delete_server_instance" calls instance.save() method which updates
vm_state to building where it should be in active state.

Fixed "test_delete_server_instance" to test deleting an instance which
is in active state and has a valid host.

Closes-Bug: #1404867
Closes-Bug: #1408527
Change-Id: Ic630ae7d026a9697afec46ac9ea40aea0f5b5ffb

commit_message:
Splitting out PKCS11 plugin

Preemptively splitting the PKCS11 plugin before removing
the HMAC and MKEK generation from barbican. This will
enable other scripts to use the PKCS11 interface without
loading the plugin. The tests were updated to reflect this
change as well.

Change-Id: I4e4a1576f217f8443b9af8ff359de6e9b0f1c42b

commit_message:
Move sysctl settings into hieradata

This will configure the sysctl settings via puppet instead of
sysctl image element.

Change-Id: Ieb129d4cbe4b6d4184172631499ecd638073564f

commit_message:
Add simplegeneric to py34 requirements

simplegeneric suppoosed to be installed by WSME, but for a some reasons
it was missed in py3 env. We can't add this library to requirements.txt,
because it missed in global requirements, so I've added simplegeneric
to the `deps` section in py34 environment.

This if a fast-and-dirty way to unblock python34 gates for ironic.

Change-Id: Ib0cddf7541defbdfe1b17448b52becf8bd4ef3de

- gate-barbican-specs-docs http://docs-draft.openstack.org/59/127659/1/check/gate-barbican-specs-docs/aa5fac6/doc/build/html/ : SUCCESS in 1m 22s'}, {'account_id': 13914, 'date': '2014-11-10 12:17:06.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1

I have use case for this when Barbican is being used directly with ZFS for filesystem/volume wrapping keys. This could be used with ZFS by specifying keysource=hex,https://... rather than keysource=raw,https://...'}, {'account_id': 10873, 'date': '2014-11-17 12:26:50.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

You should take a look at this: https://review.openstack.org/#/c/133725/

Might be relevant to this.'}, {'account_id': 6783, 'date': '2014-11-18 20:31:40.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review-2

I am giving this -2 not because I think it is a bad idea but because I think this one will be overcome by a new content type CR. At the summit we talked extensively about content type and how to handle that. When we left we decided that we need to standardize the way data is not only received by the API but also the secret store interface.

We are going to pick specific encodings for storing the different types of secrets. Symmetric keys and generic secret blobs will be Base64 encoded. Public and private keys will have a specific encoding but it is still TBD.

Let me know if that will work for you or if I need to reconsider something.'}, {'account_id': 994, 'date': '2014-11-18 21:45:06.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

That is OK, Nathan. One of my bug is also in the same line.
We need to have generic plan.
https://bugs.launchpad.net/barbican/+bug/1365187'}, {'account_id': 10873, 'date': '2015-01-27 14:27:04.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review-2

This will be addressed by the Content Types CR https://review.openstack.org/#/c/145073/ If you plan to take this forward, you could of course set this up for discussion in the weekly meetings (so you get enough audience). Else, could you abandon this CR?'}, {'account_id': 7973, 'date': '2015-05-20 16:58:50.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned

Superseded by http://specs.openstack.org/openstack/barbican-specs/specs/kilo/content-type.html'}]

Useful for 3rd party CIs where not all tempest tests pass in their configuration.

'}]
commit_message:
DNM: Add ability to use an exclusion list when selecting tempest tests

Useful for 3rd party CIs where not all tempest tests pass in their configuration.

The intention of this change is to allow moving of the exclusion lists to tempest
so if a new test is added that passes in gate it can be excluded from 3rd party
CIs without there being a period of breakage

Change-Id: I3487dfefe4a9b26b77fd5f7faf0a250fd85d35a3

commit_message:
Port glance_store to Python 3

* Use six.moves to get configparser, http_client and urllib modules
* Replace map(func, data) with [func(item) for item in data]
* Replace it.next() with next(it): it works on Python 2 and Python 3
* Replace dict.iteritems() with six.iteritems(dict)
* Replace unicode with six.text_type

Change-Id: I53ec902f344d7d57bb6f29a1c8b7a953efa0ff4e

commit_message:
Add empty settings for vCenter glance

So I think this blueprint is narrowing down to a decision on the resource naming, with  a goal of aligning as much as possible with Nova's quota API (see http://developer.openstack.org/api-ref-compute-v2-ext.html), and also distinguishing admin-only from normal user quota APIs.

One choice is to go with:
1) GET /v1/quotas for any type of users, gets their quota-set
2) GET /v1/quota-sets/{project-id} for admins only, get quota-set for that particular project. Adding ?limit=x?offset=y makes it paging
3) GET /v1/quota-class-sets/{quota-class-id} for admins only, get quota class info

Another is:
1) GET /v1/quotas ...
2) GET /v1/quota-projects/{project-id} ...
3) GET /v1/quota-classes/{quota-class-id} ...

Thoughts? Opinions? :)

Thanks, John"}, {'account_id': 7973, 'date': '2015-02-11 22:56:37.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 10:

Going with English language semantics, I personally like

/v1/quotas
/v1/project-quotas
/v1/class-quotas'}, {'account_id': 7874, 'date': '2015-02-11 23:22:38.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 10:

+1

The nova os-quota-class-sets API is a little confusing though. It appears that it is non-admin from the documentation and the policy file (why would a non-admin be allowed to set quotas ?). When I tried these in my devstack as a non-admin, it failed with a HTTP 403 though! Calling these as admin user however, worked.

More questions regarding listing quota sets (admin api) with pagination support: it is not clear to me if what Douglas commented earlier is covered by what John has specified in the last comment:

GET /v1/quota-sets  (new URI: /v1/quotas)

vs

GET /v1/quota-sets/{project-id}?limit=x&offset=y   (new URI: /v1/project-quotas/{project-id}?limit=x&offset=y)

1. Should we support one or both of these ?

2. As quotas could be one of (user/)project/class/default level, will this call list all of those ? Need to then arrive at how the response fields/structure will look like.

3. What other filters should this API take ? Filter by project-id, user, class ? 

4. Nova has this "GET /v2.1/os-quota-sets/?{tenant_id}?/defaults" to list defaults for a project. Do we need something like this ?


Have summarized the following list of API per above discussions (will use nova style payload). Please comment for changes:

User or Admin:


GET /v1/quotas  ===> to list one's own effective quotas


Admin only:


GET /v1/project-quotas?limit=x&offset=y  ===> to list all quota-sets, pagination supported

GET /v1/project-quotas/{project-id}  ==> get quotas for specific project, pagination supported

PUT /v1/project-quotas/{project-id}  ==> set quotas for a specific project

DELETE /v1/project-quotas/{project-id}  ==> remove project specific quotas

GET /v1/class-quotas/{quota-class-id}  ==> get quotas for specific class

DELETE /v1/class-quotas/{quota-class-id} ==> delete the quota class


more admin APIs (not documented by nova):

POST /v1/class-quotas/{quota-class-id}  ==> create quotas for specific class

PUT /v1/class-quotas/{quota-class-id}  ==> update quotas for specific class

Thanks for the great comments :)'}, {'account_id': 7789, 'date': '2015-02-12 15:28:46.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 10:

Hello Venkat,
I like your summarized list of APIs there. Do your questions above them apply to those though? 
Thanks, John'}, {'account_id': 7874, 'date': '2015-02-12 17:52:35.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 10:

John, my question was if there should be an admin API "GET /v1/quotas" with pagination to list all types of quotas, but this would only be a superset of the other GET APIS, so I would take that as a no. Thanks.'}, {'account_id': 7789, 'date': '2015-02-12 21:23:24.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 10:

Yeah, for simplicity and 'least surprise' I'd prefer to not have different behaviors for the GET quotas API depending on if it's an admin vs non-admin user.

Good then, it seems like we've ironed out some of the sticky issues...I'll see if others can weigh in now."}, {'account_id': 9234, 'date': '2015-02-12 23:13:36.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 10:

Just thought of a silly question - what do we do if someone sets a quota for a resource at a certain value, lets say X...but there already exist X+1 instances of that resource.  Do we reject the set of the quota?  

This is becoming a real bear of a blueprint - its bringing up a LOT of issues.  I wonder if it can be broken down more?'}, {'account_id': 7874, 'date': '2015-02-13 00:53:53.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 10:

Steve, my take is to do just minimal boundary checks for quota setting validation. My reasoning is, even if we compare against the resource counts and set the quotas, what if the quota checking is disabled for a while and enabled again ? The resource counts could then go more than the quotas right ?
Do you see any way this will impact the quota checks done at the resource creation time ?'}, {'account_id': 9234, 'date': '2015-02-13 15:33:51.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 10:

I suppose we could check at quote creation time and also at quota re-activation time - and if the quota would already be exceeded then the create/reactivate would fail.  That would need to be synchronized with that resource's own creation code as well so you couldn't end up with a race condition between creates of the resource and creates of the quota."}, {'account_id': 9234, 'date': '2015-02-13 15:34:52.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 10:

That implies that quotas would need to be "stop the world" with respect to their specified resource when they are created or reactivated.  Ugh.'}, {'account_id': 7789, 'date': '2015-02-13 16:43:14.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 10:

I would prefer to keep this one simple...so no checking first to see if resources are already above quota. The next time a resource creation is attempted after the new quota is set is when the error will happen. So keeping the quota resource concerns separate from other resources. I don't think precision is needed here, we are just trying to do a better job of resource control that what is in place now (which is none)."}, {'account_id': 7973, 'date': '2015-02-13 17:15:52.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 10:

I think that

GET /v1/project-quotas/{project-id}

since it's a single project id, it may not need paging.  Other than that Venkat's summary looks good.  Another patch with this summary should do it."}, {'account_id': 7973, 'date': '2015-02-13 17:15:59.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 10: Code-Review-1'}, {'account_id': 7874, 'date': '2015-02-13 22:35:55.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 10:

commit_message:
Add Quota support for Barbican resources

This spec aims at implementing quota support for the Barbican
resources "secrets", "orders", "containers" and "transport
keys". It proposes using the oslo.common quota implemenation
in addition to implementing the REST API changes and data model
changes.

Changed quota admin REST API to be consistent with nova quota
admin API
Removed class level quota from this spec. Another spec will
cover that.
Modifed PUT to return 204 status.
Fixed pagination field names to be consistent with rest of API.

Change-Id: I4ab94d14788e3b88cbb0a3ff3c46212f408c2b3d
Implements: blueprint quota-support-on-barbican-resources

commit_message:
Set up corosync using hostnames rather than IPs

This ensures that the hosts in Corosync and in Pacemaker are the same,
to make our cluster setup compatible with the recommended architecture.

Change-Id: Id81f315768edd24b8978b8de7093e04904591ce2
Closes-Bug: #1447497
Depends-On: Idb9ad017ffb1048f38fedbd55cc974785f6b1c38

commit_message:
Cells: Add host mapping table and object

In order to properly route RPC messages or database updates to the
proper cell when given just a host we need a mapping of host to cell.
We will be provided only a host by the scheduler or for Host API
requests.

Change-Id: Ifd37410ea0009d2ee8a5720461377bef6e83eb18

commit_message:
oslo.messaging: remove double reply

Currently, when we are  waiting for a RPC reply, for each call we
receive two AMQP messages - first one with the payload, a second one
to ensure the other have finish to send the payload.

We are going to remove the second message for RPC reply.

Co-Authored-By: Victor Sergeyev <vsergeyev@mirantis.com>

Change-Id: I42106f4948279984b4dc037ca17eb9bc1cbc8207

commit_message:
Get project basics configured

 - Update the README
   - Wrapping dogpile.cache
   - Supporting cache backends and memoization
 - Add a test-requirements.txt
 - Add a dev-requirements.txt for tox
 - Update requirements from initial requirements in the template
 - Fix template test import to use oslocache.base.BaseTestCase

Change-Id: I588a5fee5f92448ee9a0905a0973abc42e44d0b0

commit_message:
Split bootstrap of 9 slaves into two stages

Bootstrapping 9 slaves at one time reqires a lot of CPU power
(>=10 real CPU cores), so it is better to bootstrap nodes in
two stages to avoid timeouts and libvirt network failures.

Change-Id: I7b3a3ceba4859b6ce4a3af95dbbeba040abd8fff
Closes-Bug:#1455539

commit_message:
Move from UserPreference to Profile

This is just a big name swap to move away from UserPreference to Profile
so it can be properly referenced in the summit talk. See #1435953

Change-Id: Iaa45fce0c8aacc9315070f8525a13f2e43f05a9e
Closes-Bug: 1435953

commit_message:
Move identity_version to class level

Rather than having to setup the client manager by passing the identity
version, read the identity version from a class level attribute, so
that the identity version can be overwritten from there by the
identity tests.

Change-Id: Ibc6e6289c349e7b5caf0fea2d0485c8cc4b9c32a

commit_message:
Update orchestration functional tests

Update the orchestration functional tests to use the setup and
teardown.  The test cleans up after itself now, but it doesn't
wait for the deleted stack to complete which would be a good
feature, but we don't have a wait method that waits for something
to be gone.

Change-Id: Id8b06e08fb22e4af3b90c4b8ab6400378565d804

commit_message:
Provide RabbitMQ clients with a list of servers instead of VIP

This will change the way how RabbitMQ clients get to the servers,
they will not go through HAProxy anymore.

Change-Id: I522d7520b383a280505e0e7c8fecba9ac02d2c9b

I really don't think we need this. Most projects have merged the changes to remove the namespace package already, and after the summit we can release the libraries with those changes so we can proceed with merging the changes in the Oslo libraries that remove the namespace package entirely.

https://review.openstack.org/#/q/topic:bp/remove-namespace-packages+project:%255Eopenstack/oslo.*,n,z"}, {'account_id': 12000, 'date': '2015-05-16 21:33:57.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3: Code-Review-1

So I'm mostly -1 on this for a few reasons:

1. stable/juno has a cap on hacking: http://git.openstack.org/cgit/openstack/requirements/tree/test-requirements.txt?h=stable/juno#n3 so I don't see the need for H311 and H312. If we were to add a check at all, it should just be H311 in my opinion.

2. Most projects that I'm aware of (and I trust Doug is far more conscious of this than I am) have already switched away from the namespaced packages.

3. If there are projects that have reached stable/kilo and have *not* removed the use of namespaced packages, then we're going to cause their gate to fail spontaneously if we include this in an 0.10.x release.

4. The plan is to remove the namespaced packages which would make it a hard import error for anything using the liberty versions of oslo. With that in mind, H311 then becomes debt and unnecessary."}, {'account_id': 2472, 'date': '2015-05-17 12:53:45.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

commit_message:
H311, H312: add checks for oslo.* | oslo_* imports

Those checks are mutually exclusive, only one of those should be enabled
for a project.

H311 allows to forbid obsolete oslo.* imports.

H312 allows to forbid new oslo_* imports (for stable branches; disabled
by default).

Change-Id: I6f80ddb4e7b2f9bae688849e00c4c27c0d230260

commit_message:
Adds Debian testing

In the current app catalog, only the Debian testing image is
present, and not the release of 8.0.0 Jessie. This patch
fixes that, by renaming the current "Debian" into a more
explicit "Debian testing weekly build" and adds "Debian Jessie".

Change-Id: I956d0991869ff43508ac6a7b22316e3d75889984

commit_message:
Add a conditional judgement to avoid invalid dict index

Before index the job_configs by key 'args', we add a judgement
to see whether key 'args' exists.

Closes-Bug: #1456171
Change-Id: I42fa4bfe5d2b9a90833bae25bd9ac44c614fd9ce

commit_message:
isolated creadentials are not cleaned up

Due to type introduced last weak, the isolated credentials are
not claned up.
In a neutron envoriements it can mean more than 1 Gigabyte memory used
in dnsmasq and in the neutron-ns-metadata-proxy.

Change-Id: I09c538ed1139380f8cd8a662e60d69d3f605cd67

commit_message:
Add new options to baremetal config section

This change adds setting of deploy_img_dir and node_uuid baremetal
config options during tempest configuration to enable ironic w/o
glance scenario testing.
Needed for change I171e85cb8a21fae4da45028f1f798988a36f6c95

Change-Id: I6fd393390389c4c643b93198fa461fc2adc415ae

Add speed limit for wget 100k

Enlarging download time of file
to be sure file size checking
was applied during the downloading process

Fix no distributions matching with pip 6.0

pip install 'prettytable>0.7' report no distributions matching(for pip
6.0). This patch fixed the issue.

(1 comment)

So the gate failures you're hitting is part of why I said not combining things with javelin to start is the better approach. Javelin is used in the grenade jobs for gating and is basically only self tested at this point, so you have to be careful when making changes to it.

While there is overlap between the 2 tools (in that they both create resources and use yaml files with similar formats) the intent of the tools is different.

I really feel this script should be, at least for the first version, a very simple tool which just makes the raw api calls (or reuses the tempest.common.isolated_creds module) to just create the number of user tenant pairs required for running a full tempest run given a concurrency. That should be fairly simple to do as a separate thing and it'll be easier to debug. For example: https://review.openstack.org/#/c/107758/ was the start of such a tool, but it kinda got lost. Heck, you could just reuse my cheap test patch loops here: https://review.openstack.org/158511 and put it in tools so we didn't require the official clients in requirements.txt. (actually that might be better given the intended audience of the tool)

We can revisit more complex ideas like things with javelin in the future. Especially given the future of the javelin tooling isn't finalized yet, it's not the right approach to make a hard dep like this. All we need right now is a script to point people to if they need help creating accounts.yaml files."}, {'account_id': 7822, 'date': '2015-04-14 13:56:41.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

I don't think we should be creating yet another yaml syntax to describe how the accounts yaml should be created. I agree with Matt's earlier comment: "I really feel this script should be, at least for the first version, a very simple tool which just makes the raw api calls (or reuses the tempest.common.isolated_creds module) to just create the number of user tenant pairs required for running a full tempest run given a concurrency." That is all most users will want. 

This code also does not create the network resources which will be needed and it would really be nice to not have two copies of all the code in isolated_creds that is used to create isolated accounts. As far as I can see it is exactly the same thing, just done ahead of time instead of for each test class. The one difference I can see is that the optimization of not creating some network resources to avoid the cost while tempest is running is not needed in this case.

Also, the destroy function does not seem very useful because any one who creates accounts using this script and then runs tempest will need to destroy any stranded resources. We already have a cleanup script to do this and IMO users will be confused when they call destroy which deletes the users/tenants but leaves stuff behind which can no longer even be seen in some cases.'}, {'account_id': 7822, 'date': '2015-04-20 20:36:57.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5:

It's my understanding that this wasn't yet another yaml description, but a tool to create an accounts.yaml as already consumed by tempest. Am I missing something?"}, {'account_id': 1192, 'date': '2015-04-20 21:42:14.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5:

@Chris: I am not sure who is missing what but it looks like etc/accounts_spec.yaml.sample is defining a yaml syntax that says what kinds of users will be created and thus actually written to the accounts.yaml file. IMO, all that is being asked for from this script is the ability to get the same functionality as you get from using isolated tenants, but without having to give admin creds to tempest. Maybe Matt or Andrea can comment.'}, {'account_id': 5196, 'date': '2015-04-20 23:39:05.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5: Code-Review-1

So I get what you're going for here, and now totally understand why you wanted to use javelin in the previous revs. (which I misunderstood before) But, I'm in agreement with David on this, that requiring an input file to describe what to create is a bit unnecessary. This tool is intended to quickly bootstrap people who don't want to hand tempest admin privileges to enable tempest to run with tenant isolation, but don't want to sit there and create a dozen different users by hand or figure out how many of which type to create. We also plan to use it in a ci job to have devstack create an accounts file.

Realistically, all you need for this tool is a concurrency count, which gives you enough information to figure out how
many of each type of users to create to avoid starvation issues. In other words for concurrency N create: Nx2 for the regular no extra role accounts, and both of the swift role accounts, and N for any other account type. Also, having a flag to optionally enable creating admin accounts would probably be good too.

While having the input file does give you the flexibility to create a more precise set of things and can totally see the value in having something like that. I don't think it's something we need to solve with this tool. I feel like if we were to solve that we should look at leveraging something like ansible which is more appropriate for doing this kinda thing. (which is what we were planning to do with javelin)"}, {'account_id': 9377, 'date': '2015-04-21 13:03:19.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 6.'}, {'account_id': 9377, 'date': '2015-04-21 13:19:04.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5:

Change-Id: I3c313787b0f6f69edcc5ad16c6c186226f619692
'}]
commit_message:
Tool for generation user accounts from spec

Implemented:
https://etherpad.openstack.org/p/accounts-yaml-generation
This tool can be used for creating user accounts for
tempest runs in concurrency.

Basic usage:
    ./account_generator.py
	--tag foo
        -c tempest.conf
	--os-username <admin-name>
	--os-password <admin-password>
	--os-tenant-name <admin-tenant>
	-r <concurrency count>
	--with-admin (optional)
	accounts.yaml

Change-Id: I3c313787b0f6f69edcc5ad16c6c186226f619692

commit_message:
Add py34 to readme, pkg metadata, and envlist

This commit adds references explaining the current state of python 3.4
and tempest to the readme, pkg metadata, and adds an etry to the tox
envlist for running the unit tests on python 3.4.

Change-Id: I9c1e3cdf53dbae723a9fee67ad96932709d2305f

commit_message:
Update Fuel EMC plugin test to be suitable for CentOS

OS version in method for checking navicli/naviseccli packages was changed
from static "Ubuntu" to env-based settings.OPENSTACK_RELEASE option.

Change-Id: Icf53ae41a197a8dc17d2ccf0b56c6693831294b7
Implements: blueprint mos-emc-pugin-test

This patch adds possibility to download upstream docker containers. I think we shouldn't do this as a part of the build process.

We have separate steps: 
1) prepare local mirrors of upstream code
2) create fuel mirrors based on local mirrors
3) build fuel images based on fuel mirror

This patch puts logic from stage 1 to stage 2, which is wrong."}, {'account_id': 10474, 'date': '2014-11-27 16:11:54.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

Getting upstream docker images is a part of mirroring process, not build process (only applicable if USE_MIRROR=none option is set). How does it differ from getting upstream packages?'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-01-22 14:24:01.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Verified-1

commit_message:
Add sourcing of upstream docker images during mirror build.

Docker images for busybox and centos:centos6 are pulled from
upstream and put to local mirror if USE_MIRROR=none option
is set.

Change-Id: Idd27399428bb0e847eba7bbb97de1c78b3d20385
Closes-Bug: #1378833

commit_message:
Change non-flexible log rotation process

Add daily logrotation option. Replace 'size' parameter
with 'minsize' and 'maxsize'.

Change-Id: I1d323bc028d076d80fe2a2c6748a1653f0d789a5
Closes-Bug: #1436465

commit_message:
Align tests for bonding with linux bridges/bonds

In 6.1 Fuel switched to use Linux bonds and bridges for all
deployments instead of OVS ones. So we should test deployments
using all available bonding types, which do not require
special switch configuration: active-backup, balance-xor,
balance-alb, balance-tlb. Also now it's possible to use Nova
Network (both Vlan and FlatDHCP modes) with network bonds, so
modify 50% of existing cases to use it instead of Neutron.

Change-Id: Ie5d55a537ce3125a20e0926864cba5d42190cbe9
Partial-bug: #1319413
Related-bug: #1455762
Partial-implements: blueprint linux-bonds-system-tests

commit_message:
Remove pre-SQLAlchemy-0.9.7 compat utilities

Now that requirements.txt is at SQLAlchemy 0.9.7 at the minimum,
we can remove the engine_connect compatibility module as well
as part of the handle_error compatibility module.

In particular, this gives us the ability to add and remove
engine_connect events using the event API directly which
can be handy in test fixtures.

Change-Id: I48450ad9d472d4377913ad391a0f5e3ba0f1471f

commit_message:
Add a keys() method to SQLAlchemy ModelBase

With this additional method, it now possible to write directly
dict(obj), instead of dict(obj.iteritems()), to cast an object to a
dictionary.

Modify also ModelIterator: it doesn't inherit from ModelBase anymore.

Change-Id: I702be362a58155a28482e733e60539d36c039509

commit_message:
Incorrect argument order passed to swap_volume

swap_volume method in _ComputeV4Proxy has incorrect
argument ordering, due to which attach volume migration
is failing with AttributeError
Modified the _ComputeV4Proxy detach_volume to have correct
argument ordering.

Change-Id: I899c053246f9eb4ac9b13a8434161a82193d1cef
Closes-Bug: #1451860

commit_message:
Move NTP and Memacache respectively into step 1 and step 2

NTP synchronization is moved to to step 1 where initial Pacemaker
configuration is performed.

Memacached is moved to step 2 to make sure it is up before the
OpenStack services are started.

Change-Id: I84121a687ee5ddb522239ecefd4d1d76c2f910b5

commit_message:
Added cleanup for tenant quotas

Both the tenant's volume and compute quotas should
be reset when cleanup is processing a tenant.
Added two new cleanup service classes for this purpose:
VolumeQuotaService and NovaQuotaService.

Change-Id: Id4b50ca81e6b9909d94762243aaa41e303870c65

commit_message:
Do not include pending deletion node in upgradable nodes

Previously pending for deletion nodes were included in deployment
if they were selected for update, by deploying other roles

You can observe one example of this behaviour in test

Closes-Bug: 1446202
Change-Id: Ic80e1421eea6a3227fc8d890bfdbab933da72fbc

commit_message:
Check exit code for dpkg-scanpackages

Check exit code of command and separates stdout and
stderr data from pipe which prevents merging metadata with
command warning or info output in packages index file.

Change-Id: I4ac51d929ee92bd2f2796c886297b9aefc417f2e
Partial-Bug: #1455130
Closes-Bug: #1447981

commit_message:
Remove `mode` option and set it internally to ha

As multinode mode is deprecated, the only possible mode is ha. Therefore
the `mode` option for fuel cli is removed.

Change-Id: Iaafaa4e190e3ce6749f162972b0b9d60558bf400
Closes-Bug: #1456540

(3 comments)

Thanks for the well detailed and thought out spec.  I think there are some questions for folks like NetApp so I'd like to get some feedback from them.

What's your plan for quotas?  Do we deduct 2x every quota item here?  Do we create a new quota class (or let the admin create a new quota class) for replicated-volumes?

I still need to better understand what this means for all of the existing functions:
delete (implicitly break the replication setup and delete both)
clone (clone to another replicated pair, we could avoid this via groupings)
snapshot (snap on both?)

Also, the only thing I really see as a question is how best to implement this up at the scheduling portion.  See my inline comment."}, {'account_id': 4418, 'date': '2014-06-09 10:01:47.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5:

commit_message:
Add volume replication support

Enable Cinder to leverage volume replication feature available
in the storage backends (drivers).

Change-Id: Ie7866e09a4580490f57c375bc706ac22cefedc1d
Implements: blueprint volume-replication

commit_message:
Scale out heat stack

Adds a module which allows scaling nodes in a heat stack
deployed using tuskar templates - typically Overcloud in TripleO.
This module will be used from CLI/UI.

Change-Id: I284cb72b15ffd92a9e50550d84374dfe9e5f94c0

[CTX] Split context into plugins

Move openstack related contexts under rally/plugins/openstack/context/

NOTE(yfried): cleanup context is handled in next patch

Implements: blueprint split-plugins

Change-Id: Ia71193163f7d178c8a9e2904b59a1591b1e39010

commit_message:
Make functional test work with new tox env

The check-functional-dsvm-magnum gate job was failing due to the
functional tests not picking up valid OpenStack credentials.

Update how we aquire credentials -- fixes side effect of how tox 2.0
handles environment variables

Closes-Bug: #1455102
Change-Id: I56ecd8003594fd436874681670bb9ead19b95dea

commit_message:
Fix how arguments are passed to the request function

In its existing state, keystoneauth.session.request was not correctly
using keyword arguments.

    python -c 'import requests; \
               requests.Session().request("https://httpbin.org/get", \
                    method="GET")'
    Traceback (most recent call last):
      File "<string>", line 1, in <module>
    TypeError: request() got multiple values for keyword argument 'method'

Change-Id: I7a3cb78bcfe448c22a9d21f134f354e71702bba3

commit_message:
Skip only one host weight calculation

If there is only one host available, calculate the weight
make no sense because whatever the weight it is, nova will
use the host.

Closes-Bug: 1448015

Change-Id: I38aed6a6e45d24dc0daf2e96c353f394f3ef5e3f

commit_message:
Drop v2 and v3 tokens clients

Token clients have been migrated to tempest_lib.
All their consumers in tempest already use the tempest_lib version.
Drop them from tempest.

Change-Id: I3a16a24863162c8691c9125700ffa58eaebc1a57

is added

commit_message:
Add CLI smoke functional tests for containers

Added tests and behaviors for containers.  Also refactored the
PrettyTable parsing to make it more generic so we can use it with
more than just secrets.

Change-Id: Icf3a462d6f24ce887977c07ed310b39c9d928a29

(3 comments)

One value for users is explained in the linked bug: if a devtest run dies part-way through (eg, because of a power outage after the undercloud build, or because disk space is exhausted part way through an overcloud build), it's not possible to continue - because the settings aren't written out until the end, the deployer has to start over.

Writing out the file at the start would allow interrupted builds to be resumed.

Another value: our current docs tell the user they might want to create a devtestrc and put some customised values in it, but to find out what values can be customised involves trawling through the docs/code. If we wrote tripleorc out at the start of the run, I think it will make it a little easier for deployers to figure out what they can tweak. For instance, this might make it easier to discover that it's a good idea to specify a local proxy to cache cloud images and packages being downloaded.

But greghaynes has a point - currently we're just serialising the defaults. To make this more useful, any modifications to the existing file need to be read in at the start of devtest_variables.sh

I'm not sure whether it makes sense to try to automatically find and source the file; or if it would make more sense to tell the user to always source the file - or maybe it would make more sense to have a --config-file option for the user to pass.

From the point of view of supporting a deployer who is deploying multiple environments, a --config-file option might be the cleanest. On the other hand, I think multiple deployed environments currently require that you have a different $TRIPLEO_ROOT for each environment - if that's the case, simply searching in $TRIPLEO_ROOT might suffice."}, {'account_id': 12459, 'date': '2015-02-05 21:20:35.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 10.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-02-05 21:21:58.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 10: Verified-1

commit_message:
Write tripleorc near start of devtest run

Currently, tripleorc doesn't get written until devtest_end.sh is run.
This means that if devtest fails prior to the end, the tripleorc won't
get written. This change adds an additional write of the tripleorc so
it will get written before a failure may occur. To facilitate writing
tripleorc early, I've had to move the assignment of some variables to
devtest_variables.sh. I've also refashioned devtest_end.sh into the
more generic devtest_write.sh for reusability.

partial-bug: 1298949
Change-Id: I7390a5585b078fda0b15ce28d032cf6ba52609f7

commit_message:
Add os-testr to global requirements list

This commit adds os-testr to global requirements since it will be
the default runner of testr for most projects' tests.

Change-Id: Ia399c65e62c2306c9a2d082c6219fcb030b5946b

commit_message:
Only create a TokenClient if api_v2 is enabled

Token clients should only be setup if the corresponding API
version is marked as available. If they are configured as
available but the URI is not set, the configuration is invalid.

Change-Id: Ib2885dbb04af3dc12724fe50bed8ce73ec3c426c
Closes-bug: #1451987

commit_message:
Bring Redhat support to acceptance tests

OpenStack Infra has jobs to run this on both Ubuntu Trusty and CentOS7.

* Add minitest to Gemfile (dependency to run beaker on centos - see
  http://projects.theforeman.org/issues/2650 for details)
* separate nodepool files to have trusty & centos7 support in OS infra
* basic_manila_spec: add case for repo configuration and support
  RH systems.
* rabbitmq: install module from source
* apt: pin the module

Change-Id: I03f7cd95809eba8fb6b1679a5669fbc72a9bc82c
Closes-bug: #1444736

commit_message:
Fix the docker build image issue

The python cryptography issue, check
http://www.123code.blogspot.com/2014/10/fixed-installing-python-cryptography.html

The ubuntu pip issue, check
http://stackoverflow.com/questions/27341064/how-do-i-fix-importerror-cannot-import-name-incompleteread

Closes-Bug: #1455420
Change-Id: I8cb78f990c08cb527ebce3fa720537b5c03eb942

commit_message:
Remove self.pre_run calls in packaging.py

pre_run was a method of _PipInstallTestRequires class which was
removed by https://review.openstack.org/#/c/181785/.

Change-Id: I2118f2a96d0c9984797424e5dda47547c8e24621
Closes-Bug: #1456663

commit_message:
Generate log warning messages when PUTs are smaller than segment size

Added a warning message to notify when the PUT objects are smaller
than the given segment size in the EC Storage Policy.

Change-Id: I2e0c814eed2b771a500e01275c7af549ab1ebaca

commit_message:
Make backlog usable

* Link to Liberty template
* Add empty backlog/approved directory
* Update backlog index
* Since we cannot have an empty approved directory, link to
  backlog-template for now.

Change-Id: I5f91e28f8d5d55397ba7d9f0c9881cce477a4e6b

commit_message:
Add option to set Horizon memcache driver to correct template

Changeset Ice172b07fa765daff1a2e0feea7a5bee2f826b88 introduced changes
to local_settings.py template not used during deployment. This commit
reverts those and ports them to the template used in actual deployment.

Additionally some of ERB tags were not substituted or iterated correctly,
resulting in broken Horizon config.

Change-Id: I2092cf2a8c7407b814abcef28e843cf2da84444e
Closes-Bug: 1367767

Not thrilled with this. The outcome from the mailing list was that using it for python3 installs sounded like a good idea, but this does nothing to do that. Nor do we have a great answer for that until markerlib comes out. I'd like to see that sorted out before we land this and accidentally migrate something in the gate that we were not expecting to migrate."}, {'account_id': 9107, 'date': '2015-05-04 17:38:37.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

> Nor do we have a great answer for that until markerlib comes out. I'd like to see that sorted out before we land this and accidentally migrate something in the gate that we were not expecting to migrate.

Environment markers don't work in all cases in requirements, but it's possible to use requirements-py3.txt to get different dependencies on Python 3. It's not something new.

I would prefer to use mysqlclient on Python 2 and Python 3 because it is also better on Python 2 (to get bugfixes)."}, {'account_id': 6476, 'date': '2015-05-04 22:51:46.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review+1

Monty, the issue is that MySQL-python is unmaintained, while mysqlclient seems to be. I don't agree that having MySQL-python for Py2 and mysqlclient for Py3 is "the outcome" of the mainling list discussion, this is only the opinion of Mike Bayer, and I don't agree. I'm on the side of Victor here.'}, {'account_id': 9107, 'date': '2015-05-05 13:06:41.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

I wrote a patch to replace MySQL-python with mysqlclient (on Python 2 *and* Python 3) test requirement in nova:
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/180128/'}, {'account_id': 11816, 'date': '2015-05-05 15:58:10.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

I'm not sure what it means to have both mysqlclient *and* mysql-python in the requirements file at the same time, since they use the same module namespace (correct me if I'm wrong on that).

Also, this would mean that distributions would need to *uninstall* their current mysql-python packages to make room for this one (again, I'm not a distro expert, but that's what it seems like, correct me if I'm wrong.  i'll try to ask around downstream here to see what the implications are).

AFAICT mysql-python is still maintained as far as critical bugfixes.  Other than "does not support eventlet", which mysqlclient has just as much, I'm not familiar with any bugs in it that are impacting openstack applications right now (again, I'd love information on this).

As Python 3 is where things are headed, as installations migrate to Python 3 which is still more bleeding edge, they can also upgrade to the less proven MySQL client as well. 

if *anything* were to change in Python2, it should be that we go to PyMySQL, or drop eventlet.   Using another MySQL driver that is just as broken with our concurrency model as the current one, *plus* introducing the packaging issue and whatever instabilities are present by the fact that this is a much more actively changing driver, seems crazy.'}, {'account_id': 9107, 'date': '2015-05-05 16:26:38.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

> I'm not sure what it means to have both mysqlclient *and* mysql-python in the requirements file at the same time, since they use the same module namespace (correct me if I'm wrong on that).

Dims has a similar upgrade plan for suds and the situation is very similar. suds is not more maintained whereas suds-jurko is a fork and it is maintained. Both libraries provide the same Python module (suds). suds and suds-jurko are in global requirements to have a smooth transition plan.

FYI I just proposed patches for oslo.vmware, cinder and nova to replace suds with suds-jurko on Python 2 and Python 3 (suds-jurko was already used for Python 3 in oslo.vmware). When these patches will be merged, suds can be removed from global requirement.

I propose the same plan to replace mysql-python with mysqlclient.


> Also, this would mean that distributions would need to *uninstall* their current mysql-python packages to make room for this one (again, I'm not a distro expert, but that's what it seems like, correct me if I'm wrong. i'll try to ask around downstream here to see what the implications are).

See Thomas Goirand's email (Debian packager):
http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2015-May/063225.html

"I don't see what it would break. If I do (...) everything is fine, and python-mysqlclient becomes another implementation of the same thing."


> AFAICT mysql-python is still maintained as far as critical bugfixes.

The last commit was done in january 2014:
https://github.com/farcepest/MySQLdb1/commits/master

The maintainter didn't reply to my emails (yet). There are now 32 open issues and 25 pending pull requests.

Which critical bugfixes were fixed recently?'}, {'account_id': 11816, 'date': '2015-05-05 16:45:35.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

> Which critical bugfixes were fixed recently?

what critical bugfixes *are* there?  

I've proposed to mysqlclient that they change the import name of their package: https://github.com/PyMySQL/mysqlclient-python/issues/44  Then the issues here go away entirely.

It should not be impossible to run both DBAPIs at the same time, and using the same name here is bad form.   The psycopg2cffi driver for pypy is the only psycopg2 that you can use on pypy, yet they still went with a different import name.

As far as linux distros, I had missed Thomas' reply to me.   But I'm not sure how we're comfortable with the idea that one package would silently replace the other, and not even deterministically!  What if I install the mysqlclient package before the mysql-python one?  Now I have the *old* version in place.  How is that to be accounted for?

Basically if mysqlclient becomes a good python citizen and picks their own module name, go nuts.  We all saw what a nightmare it was when distribute (necessarily) had to use the same module name as setuptools."}, {'account_id': 11816, 'date': '2015-05-05 19:13:31.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

I'm trying to get info from Django core devs now who apparently also have started recommending mysqlclient.   Andy Dustman is a real person so I'd like to get some indication that he is OK with, or at least somewhat aware, that his package is going to be wiped off the map once linux distros start replacing it, e.g. some kind of semi-confirmation of sorts that we can consider MySQL-python to be "dead".'}, {'account_id': 9107, 'date': '2015-05-19 22:01:38.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned'}]

commit_message:
Add mysqlclient dependency

mysqlclient is a MySQL driver supporting Python 2 and Python 3.

mysqlclient is a fork of MySQL-python. It was created by INADA Naoki,
who is also the author of PyMySQL (a pure Python driver for MySQL).
mysqlclient adds Python 3 support, some new features and various
bugfixes.

mysqlclient and MySQL-python are exclusive, they cannot be used at the
same time (with the same Python version), since both packages provide
the same Python module ("MySQLdb"). An application can use MySQL-python
on Python 2 and mysqlclient on Python 3, or mysqlclient on Python 2 and
Python 3.

mysqlclient is distributed under the same license than MySQL-Python: GNU
GPL.

Add also the license of MySQL-python which was missing.

Change-Id: I109f3726fff27de2b61bc3423615207c12bb0af2

commit_message:
Add unit tests for ML2 DVR port binding and fix PortContext inconsistencies

Extends the existing ML2 port binding unit tests to cover the
distributed port bindings used for DVR. Within the test mechanism
driver, bindings are tracked per-host, and additional assertions are
added.

Fixes issues with PortContext attributes that were exposed by these
new tests. Adds new vif_type, original_vif_type, vif_details, and
original_vif_details PortContext attributes, similar to the exising
host, original_host, status, and original_status attributes, to
reflect host-specific details of distributed (or normal) port
bindings. Also fixes original_host and original_status to return None
when in the context of an operation other than an update, and fixes
original_host to reflect the specific host being bound for a
distributed port.

Closes-bug: 1453943
Closes-bug: 1453955
Change-Id: I467db0d48e4b82fdaad8d851e294e639a84a8160

commit_message:
Add sphinxcontrib-blockdiag

This has the potential of allowing architecture diagrams being written
in markup and automatically transformed to images.

sphinxcontrib-seqdiag from the same parent project is already a dependency
so adding blockdiag should not be controversial.

commit_message:
Move policy options to the oslo_policy group in the config

Having the policy-related options in the DEFAULT section in the config
has been deprecated in favor of having an oslo_policy group. This CR
effectively changes that in the configuration we give as an example.

Change-Id: If5433f6fd5b295e5e758a75ea2eac3892e78e681

(2 comments)

Hi Anant and Thomas, thanks for the comments:
regarding the -P suggestion, I still think there might be a room for this. In the future, other stack actions might enable different parameters, having a different flag for each one, (where some of the actions might have more than a single parameter), might get messy.
I see that in the current blueprint we only have one flag and using the name explicitly is cleaner, however I'm not sure we should limit ourselves.
However, If you still feel uncomfortable with this, and think it should be changed, then Ill change it."}, {'account_id': 7193, 'date': '2015-04-20 09:55:12.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

Hi Noa, in general I would be fine with a "parameters bags like" option (i.e. being able to to provide a number of parameters as done with -P today). My only reservation to using the -P option is that this is solely used for providing parameters defined in the 'parameters' section of a template, so a very clear definition of what -P does. If we change this to a model where some of the things in -P go to the stack, some other things go to the engine, this is a bit unclean IMO.'}, {'account_id': 15353, 'date': '2015-04-20 10:39:58.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

OK, I'll change the flag to --level instead -P."}, {'account_id': 15353, 'date': '2015-04-20 14:24:06.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 5.'}, {'account_id': 15353, 'date': '2015-04-20 14:29:32.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 6.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-04-20 14:38:10.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6: Verified+1

changed -P flag to --level'}, {'account_id': 7193, 'date': '2015-04-20 14:56:46.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6: Code-Review+2'}, {'account_id': 9408, 'date': '2015-04-20 15:03:04.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 16002, 'date': '2015-04-20 15:36:27.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 12259, 'date': '2015-04-21 04:44:14.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6: Code-Review+1

LGTM. Some thoughts:

1.I am still not very clear on how the unlock operation will know whether to go for unlocking the resources or not. You may have to store the value of level somewhere or some hint is needed to be stored.

2. You can always use the --key=value kind of options for the command, if you feel that there might be more "flags" to define the behavior of lock/unlock.'}, {'account_id': 15353, 'date': '2015-04-21 08:04:29.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6:

Hi Anant,
I think that using the stack resource's state should be enough. 
A resource's state will only be locked in case the flag was --level=all (for any resource that is not a "nested stack").
then when the user initiates "unlock" we will know which resources need to be unlocked by their states.
do you think I'm missing something?
thanks'}, {'account_id': 12259, 'date': '2015-04-21 10:58:30.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6:

In that case you will have to load the resources to and check whether they were locked. I was thinking we could do away with that in case of --level=stacks, if we have a hint that resources are not locked.'}, {'account_id': 8833, 'date': '2015-04-22 02:27:48.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6:

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 15353, 'date': '2015-04-26 09:00:24.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6:

(1 comment)

Hi Anant,
IMO this the natural way to do it, 
looking at the DB model, the only place I could think to store this information is: as two separate values in the action column, such as (LOCK_ALL, LOCK_STACKS), which seems a bit off to me.
The other option is to add another column to the table especially for this, this seems a bit redundant since we can actually have the information already from the resources.
Do you feel that one of these options is valid and better than iterating over the resources, or have any other suggestions?'}, {'account_id': 12606, 'date': '2015-04-30 18:16:25.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6: Code-Review-1

(3 comments)

I have a few questions, see inline.'}, {'account_id': 15353, 'date': '2015-05-04 10:40:01.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6:

(3 comments)

Hi Miguel
I hope my inline comments answer you questions.
if they do please kindly remove the -1.
thanks
Noa Koffman'}, {'account_id': 12606, 'date': '2015-05-04 16:10:39.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 6: -Code-Review

(2 comments)

@noa, the intention with my questions was to point out things that I think should be included in the spec, not just to get the answers in replies. My opinion is that the answers you provided should be incorporated in the spec so that everyone has a chance to review them.

In particular you have flagged this spec as APIImpact, so the API should be very well described so that we in the API-WG can give a proper review.

Also there is no mention of how a failed lock or unlock can leave the stack in an inconsistent locking state, and that it is expected the client should issue a retry to correct the situation.

I'm going to remove my -1 in case others think what I'm asking is unreasonable, but I will hold off on a positive review until you revise the spec."}, {'account_id': 12259, 'date': '2015-05-05 07:47:06.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6:

(3 comments)

commit_message:
Spec for Add lock and unlock stack actions.

While stack is locked heat will not allow any actions on the stack to
take place, and will ignore signals that invoke actions such as scaling.

blueprint lock-stack

APIImpact
DocImpact

Change-Id: I3ecad2e61deb2f7f6b69b3fcc5a948614c446b43

[{'created': '2015-05-19 11:05:28.000000000', 'message': "Bump pbr cap to <2.0

Hacking's pbr cap of <1.0 is breaking things (see bug for a lot more
detail). Trunk hacking has already moved to the new pbr cap, but it
there is a backwards incompatible change on trunk
(I819d2069f169cabd1fcf333057a80790678e3745) that prevents us from
releasing 0.10.2 from there. So I created a 0.10.x branch and am
changing the pbr requirement here so that we can cut hacking 0.10.2 to
fix the bug.

Change-Id: I77f2b7e661c4de067e39596765d36a4463a2d143
Closes-Bug: #1456376
(cherry picked from commit bc4b1118e155784bc306c01733375ffec56b89b3)
"}, {'created': '2015-05-19 13:42:05.000000000', 'message': "Bump pbr cap to <2.0

Hacking's pbr cap of <1.0 is breaking things (see bug for a lot more
detail). Since projects are still using hacking 0.9.x bump the PBR cap
to unbreak projects still on 0.9.x.

Change-Id: I77f2b7e661c4de067e39596765d36a4463a2d143
Closes-Bug: #1456376
(cherry picked from commit bc4b1118e155784bc306c01733375ffec56b89b3)
"}]
commit_message:
Bump pbr cap to <2.0

Hacking's pbr cap of <1.0 is breaking things (see bug for a lot more
detail). Since projects are still using hacking 0.9.x bump the PBR cap
to unbreak projects still on 0.9.x.

Change-Id: I77f2b7e661c4de067e39596765d36a4463a2d143
Closes-Bug: #1456376
(cherry picked from commit bc4b1118e155784bc306c01733375ffec56b89b3)

commit_message:
Add timeout to restore

On restore containers need to apply all settings. We need
to wait when it happens.

Change-Id: Iaf159736d68774bd8b785af7078d4e9f17b1a30c
Closes-Bug: #1448211

commit_message:
add property 'delay_while_up' for port or bond

In some cases (for example slow LACP bonds or optical links)
system administrator need make delay between interface stay UP and
continue of boot process. This option allow make delay after interface UP.

Closes-bug: #1441435
Change-Id: I5013edc915b78687e1eebe5c61fe5a9befd222f6

commit_message:
WIP: refactor the PUT method into separate classes

For now there's only the ReplicatedObjectController class,
similar to the changes in feature/ec branch.

The Base class containes all public API handling, while
ReplicatedObjectController only handles data transfer
to object server.

Change-Id: Id855d5ed7365f0becf9d1549313cfe6f045d7282
Signed-off-by: Thiago da Silva <thiago@redhat.com>

commit_message:
Support for running Nova with oslo.rootwrap daemon

Nova is being enhanced to use rootwrap as a daemon. For this effort,
we need an additional entry for nova-rootwrap-daemon in the
sudoers.d/ directory.

Needed by:
I57dc2efa39b86fa1fa20730ad70d056e87617c96

Change-Id: I80c7b9dd8e9e0f940aa4e54a95b241dfc40d3574

commit_message:
Infer rootwrap arguments from project

We can infer the binary and configuration paths just from the project
name and expanding this to the known *_DIR & *_BIN_DIR variables.  A
similar thing is done for policyd settings

Change-Id: I7c6a9fa106948ae5cbcf52555ade6154623798f1

commit_message:
ngReorg - create 'widgets' module

This commit collects UI components into a new
'horizon.framework.widgets' module. It also standardizes
the naming pattern for .scss files and makes them hierarchical.

This is one step in a larger effort to restructure the Angular
source. See https://review.openstack.org/#/c/176152/ for the
full set of planned changes.

Change-Id: I2edabd6c43f811a4bb2e3abe982dbc24958ddf93
Partial-Bug: #1454880

commit_message:
Take Daemon stdin/stdout/stderr args as file objects

Previously Daemon constructor took stdin/stdout/stderr as
paths (defaulting to '/dev/null') and opened them as regular files.
This greatly limits the type of filehandles supported (no pipes, for
example), and doesn't allow simple things like reusing existing fds.

This change switches to accepting file objects rather than strings,
and uses a sentinal value to represent the previous "open /dev/null"
default behaviour.

Change-Id: I51b36ce912194abd89ed46fad9943802f271444a

commit_message:
ngReorg - create 'util' module

This commit collects some utilties into a new
'horizon.framework.util' module

This is one step in a larger effort to restructure the Angular
source. See https://review.openstack.org/#/c/176152/ for the
full set of planned changes.

Partial-Bug: #1454880

commit_message:
Add functional test job for cinderclient

We have functional tests merged in python-cinderclient now,
this patch adds the job to project-config to configure and
run.

Start of as experimental to make sure things are working.

Change-Id: Ie87b0d687d6be5ca74f4e3a110aa5cc754aa7085

commit_message:
FlashSystem reports error while running tests with multi-thread

There was an issue while running initialize_connection/
terminate_connection/_map_vdisk_to_host/_unmap_vdisk_from_host in
parallel threads.

This fix adds lock into these functions and removes incorrect
timer.stop().

Change-Id: If433522bc7799e16a918ba7c5b300b7333e430a8
Close-bug: 1452721

[{'created': '2015-05-19 16:42:42.000000000', 'message': 'Update hacking to 0.10.x series

Get current release of hacking both for new features/rules and to
address a problem where older hacking requires and older version of pbr
than the version of pbr under test. This will get the pep8 jobs working
again for pbr by removing the <1.0 pbr requirement in hacking.

Change-Id: I303db998e3aa64468a931f7e8985592b3446a1c8
'}]
commit_message:
Update hacking to 0.10.x series

Get current release of hacking both for new features/rules and to
address a problem where older hacking requires and older version of pbr
than the version of pbr under test. This will get the pep8 jobs working
again for pbr by removing the <1.0 pbr requirement in hacking.

Change-Id: I303db998e3aa64468a931f7e8985592b3446a1c8

commit_message:
Repo availability verification using public network

Generate config for repo availability setup with public network.
Config should contain:
- not used ip address from public network
- vlan tag in case network is tagged (0 will be used otherwise)
- gateway of public network
- list of repo urls
- iface where public network should be configured

Partial-Bug: 1439686
Change-Id: Ia588263730b9085650b10cc1f05edefcb43077cc

commit_message:
Revert "Merge "Fix get_monitor function and local vars for rabbit OCF""

This reverts commit 0562e2ae27c1d6b2e027e63c5af4e1153f44224b, reversing
changes made to 5fd379f0cd8106808ab9fc098ca1094c7d91041a.

The issue is that by design, the start action will start beam process
and stop the rabbit app, unless master promoted or slave joined cluster.
We have to revert aforementioned commit as it introduced a regression
to the action monitor, which is to report "Not running", when rabbit app
is stopped.

Related-bug: #1455761
Change-Id: I686c620092909351c910598aeef0dcc73d2da080

commit_message:
Add repo availability verification with network setup

Repo availability with and without setup will return 
response in next format:

  {uid=> '3', status=> 1, out=>{failed_urls=>[...]}, err=>"Error message"}

Partial-Bug: 1439686

commit_message:
Adapt fuel-package-updates to handle metadata only for repos

Summary of changes:
* New option --no-download (-N) to skip downloads
* New option --make-default (-m) to update default repo config
* New distro ubuntu-baseos for handling trusty
* ubuntu-baseos can only be used for metadata, but not download (-N)
* --clear-upstream-repos switch to replace ubuntu* repos with trusty
* added default mirror URLs for ubuntu and centos
* --apply now can use --env or --make-default or both
* Updated release to 2014.2.2-6.1 (was 2014.2-6.1)
* Fixed HTTP port for repo to 8080 (was 8000)
* --baseurl now represents full URL to repo (was baseurl+release)
* Added global vars fuel_ver and openstack_release

Closes-Bug: #1454624
Closes-Bug: #1455159
blueprint package-fuel-components

Change-Id: I3ecdc3dee2675e2c63fc480b77df3e550048e669

commit_message:
Fixing pep8 gate PBR issue

Having the sitepackages declaration in our tox.ini is causing
gate failures due to a PBR package conflict. Removing to resolve
the issue.

Change-Id: Ib9d9c5881ac4857d89bfa7ac0badbbb50984e89f
Closes-Bug: #1456664

commit_message:
Revert "Add information on new LXD hypervisor to the list of supported hypervisors Remove superfluous whitespaces"

The hypervisor is not supported according to the wiki page, so it should not have been added.

This reverts commit 60af8eabede32b9aeddde377ece7196dad22d256.

Change-Id: I5b815afed1ea79f837fa04b943bcbc9174ed0307

commit_message:
Restart mcollective at the end of cloud-init magic

We use mcollective cloud-init module to configure
mcollective service. This module runs the command
'service mcollective start' which does nothing
if the service is already running (which is the actual case).
So, we can end up with mcollective unable to see
config file changed made by cloud-init and hence
prevent mcollective from being able to connect to
rabbit.

This patch restarts mcollective at the end of cloud-init run.

Closes-Bug: #1455489
Change-Id: I9ea122acc168120596bf48f378e92874936bcbe1

commit_message:
Prevent nailgun-agent/cloud-init collision

This patch prevents nailgun-agent from doing anything
until cloud-init has finished its magic.

/etc/nailgun-agent/nodiscover file is created during provisioning stage
and then it is removed in /etc/rc.local which guarantees
that nailgun-agent doesn't change mcollective config at the
same time when cloud-init does this. Otherwise, we can
end up with corrupted mcollective config.

Related-Patch: I5fca4ca39abdc273f6958f2643fae6c5c99fba68
Change-Id: If8d1252e6d351ad073de26afc13a19de76f531fb
Closes-Bug: #1449186

commit_message:
Removed sync from reboot_nodes

The thing is we reboot nodes one by one
sleeping couple seconds between subsequent reboot RPC calls.
Sometimes we spend quite long time doing this, time
which is enough for one or more nodes to reboot.
We then call sync method (which is absolutely unnecessary)
and cobbler removes all tftp configs and creates them
again. And sometimes a node can not get the config that
makes it stick on boot asking a user to press any key.

Change-Id: I3ac5a887725411abdfbe1209b8e9f986fbb62666
Closes-Bug: #1456247

commit_message:
Moved nodiscover to /etc/nailgun-agent

We create /etc/nailgun-agent/nodiscover during
provisioning and then this file is assumed to be
removed in /etc/rc.local which guarantees
that nailgun-agent doesn't change mcollective config at the
same time when cloud-init does this. Otherwise, we can
end up with corrupted mcollective config.

Former location of this file /var/run/nodiscover assumes
it is removed at the beginning of the boot process while
we need it to be in place at least until cloud-init
has finished its magic. For details see
http://www.pathname.com/fhs/pub/fhs-2.3.html#VARRUNRUNTIMEVARIABLEDATA

Related-Patch: If8d1252e6d351ad073de26afc13a19de76f531fb
Change-Id: I5fca4ca39abdc273f6958f2643fae6c5c99fba68
Related-Bug: #1449186

commit_message:
fix network setup on evacuate

As reported in bug #1430042 when using evacuate + neutron virtual
machines fail to evacuate because of a failure to update port
bindings.  A similar issue applies to FloatingIP setup for
nova-network.

A related fix was proposed in
https://answers.launchpad.net/ubuntu/+source/nova/+question/257358
and seemed to be fixing users.

This handles things a bit differently in order to more cleanly
use existing code.

Change-Id: Iafa6d2e9eb76ea0389067c939f21ac2181df6f95
Closes-Bug: #1430042
